title: For Sale:  Custom-Built Bedford County Pennsylvania Long Rifle .40 with  double set trigger, numerous period brass inlays and ornate floral raised relief carving
postcontent:
Custom-Built Bedford County Pennsylvania Long Rifle .40 with double set trigger.

Excellent looking tiger curly maple stock with brass patchbox, numerous period brass inlays and ornate floral raised relief carving on both sides of the stock.
The carving on this rifle is more than the typical "C" Scroll found on most of these period rifles.

This rifle is a great shooter, well balanced at the mid-length of the rifle at ramrod entry in the stock.


Bedford County Information:
A distinguishing feature of the Bedford County rifle is its length. These rifles tended to be quite long and were constructed on maple stocks of excellent quality. Numerous inlays of silver and brass decorated the length of the stock.
The rifles often used a patchbox of modified floral design held with six to nine screws. The barrel was pinned to the stock with three or four pins, depending on its length, and the pins were set through brass or silver inlays.

The cheek piece usually featured some inletting on this type rifle and almost all of the inlays included a certain amount of engraving. Relief carving in a vine pattern that seems to cover and wind around the stock seems typical of rifles from this region. The butt seems to angle down from the wrist in a gradual slope. The wood used for Bedford County rifle stocks was always of the finest quality obtainable and carving and inlays highlighted the luster of the wood grain.

Some of the men who carried these rifles ranged through the Appalachian Mountains to open and settle new lands. The Bedford Rifle played an important part in the heritage of the families who settled this area. Hanging over a fireplace, it was an object of pride, and in the hands of its owner it was an important and efficient tool for survival.

The Buyer is responsible for any shipping fees, as well as any additional fees from Paypal. This is an antique firearm but uses a modern style cartridge and if shipped it does require an FFL. 
The Buyer is also responsible to check if it is legal to own this item in their area and should do so prior to placing a bid. 
** PAYMENT due within 5 days of auction end. Item not shipped until funds clear.

title: For Sale:  Pair of Pretty Czechs!! (Firearms of Course)
postcontent:
As I get close to finishing the sale of my lifelong military firearms collection - I have two beautiful Czech pieces left.    

The first is a VZ52 SHE rifle made in 1955 and chambered in the 7.62 x 45 round which is more powerful than the 7.62 x39, but less powerful than the 7.62 Nato.    

I bought this rifle 27 years ago from an elderly gentleman who had a rather extensive collection. He told me that he personally brought it back from a trip abroad in the 70's and that it was an arsenal refurbed rifle that was going to be exported to the US to one of our big importers. However he said he purchased and brought it here himself before it was sold to the importer. Truth is that I can't confirm or deny his story, but I've looked it over pretty closely and don't see any of your typical import stamps.    

The rifle is in great shape, and I'd have to rate it a solid 95% with regard to overall condition. The metal is in excellent and so is the wood. There is no rust or pitting on the metal and no gouges or cracks in the wood. The bore is excellent as well.    

Over my 37 years of collecting I've only see a few VZ52's that were on par with this one. Many of these that came over in the 1990's were so beat up that the importer elected to use a spray on plastic "bed liner" material to refurb them which created one ugly sucker in my opinion.    

Rifle comes with the correct sling, plus a complete and original cleaning kit that stows in a compartment in the buttstock. Additionally there is a spare mag that looks brand new. These mags are tough to find and often cost $75 or more when you do.    

Finally there is 11 boxes of original CZECH 7.62 x 45 ammo included. Ammo is packed in 15 round boxes and has a lacquered steel cases. It's also very magnetic meaning it has a steel penetrating core. I know Numrich used to sell a chamber insert that converted this rifle over to fire the 7.62 x 39 round. They used to cost about $25, and were easy to install. This was all that was needed as the factory mags work with the slightly shorter 7.62 x 39 cartridge.    

The other pretty Czech is a CZ52 pistol chambered in the very potent 7.62 x 25 round. Pistol was originally made in 1954, and was arsenal refurbished after it was retired. It was imported to the US by Century Arms in the early 90's and I am the original owner since import. The pistol is unfired since imported so it's in excellent condition. Metal & grips are 98%+, and bore is mirror bright.    

It comes with a correct original holster that is excellent, correct rope lanyard, cleaning rod and three original magazines.    

Additionally there is an assortment of 7.62 x 25 ammo from all over the place that I collected over the years:    

(1) 70 round box brass case Polish surplus    

(2) 40 round boxes Czech brass case surplus on eight round stripper clips (this ammo is steel core magnetic)    

(5) 16 round paper packs Bulgarian brass case surplus (also steel core penetrator)    

(2) 50 round boxes PPU commercial brass case, non-corrosive with lead core.  

All together 340 rounds    

Both the rifle and pistol come with reprinted operating manuals.    

Asking price for the rifle with accessories and ammo is $800  and $500 for the pistol, accessories and ammo. Or if you'd like them both I'd take $1200 for everything. This is a local sale with pickup in the Brandon area to a Florida resident who is at least 21 years old.    

I'm only allowed 3 pictures so I'd be happy to provide more to a serious buyer.    

If you happen to have a SIG 522, Beretta ARX .22, GSG STG44 .22, or an ISSC MK22 rifle that you'd like to trade - I would be interested in working out a deal.  

Thanks for looking.

CRAZY LOW REDUCTION! The first $425 takes the P380 & the holster. It kills me to have to sell it all, but I marvel over the fact that nobody has snatched this up at the previous price. 

A truly special firearm! Anyone who knows better, knows that the Kahr P380 is one of the best (and best-made) 380s on the market. (Don't believe the hype on the CW380--it's inferior to the P-model in almost every way).

This gun is all broken-in with only 600 rounds put through it. Like-new condition. Includes original foam cut-out case with all paperwork and two mags. 

PLUS, it comes with the most-excellent (AND UN-USED) Sneaky Pete concealed-carry holster. I never got my CC permit, so the holster is brand new, selling on Amazon for $55. Pete is made of leather, has a strong metal belt clip that won't slip off, a magnetic flap, and is made especially for the Kahr. The internal structure of the holster prevents you from retrieving the Kahr with your finger on the trigger, making it a very safe pull. It's very slim and is hardly noticeable with a light shirt or jacket hanging over it. Now I'm moving to where I can't take any guns, so this is purely a must-sell situation and is breaking my heart! Price includes the Kahr, original case, and the Sneaky Pete holster.

$425 is over $250 less than I paid for gun and holster not too many months ago. It's still practically new, with only enough rounds through it to meet Kahr's recommended break-in period.  If you pass up this offer, you'll be singing the blues later. 

I'm moving abroad and *have* to sell--I can't take it where I'm moving. Do us both a favor and snatch up the best 380 out there, for a price that *seems* too good to be true, but in this case it *is* true.
